  "learnings_before": "- Valproate (syrup, tablet or dispersible) is stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies, costs ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg dose, and is the preferred first‑line AED for children ≤ 2 years with focal or generalized seizures unless a contraindication is documented.  \n- Recommended therapeutic range for valproate is 20–30 mg/kg/day; doses outside this window should be adjusted only after confirming a serum valproate level < 50 µg/mL and normal baseline liver enzymes (ALT/AST < 2× ULN) and platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L.  \n- If a prescription section lists a drug and dose, the default action is to continue that regimen unchanged unless the clinical notes explicitly state a dose change, adverse event, or laboratory abnormality.  \n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory cases when valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable or contraindicated; it is avoided in children with spastic cerebral palsy because sedation occurs in ~30 % of such patients.  \n- Clobazam is not on the Ugandan Essential Medicines List for pediatric epilepsy and is rarely stocked; it should only be used if specifically prescribed by the clinician and serum clobazam levels are available (valproate co‑administration markedly increases clobazam concentrations).  \n- Levetiracetam is an effective non‑aromatic alternative; its cost is 2–3 × that of valproate and dispersible tablets may be intermittently unavailable, so it is considered only when valproate is contraindicated, poorly tolerated, or unavailable in any formulation.  \n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) should be avoided in any child with a prior drug‑induced rash; if a rash history exists, the regimen defaults to valproate ± levetiracetam.  \n- Adherence ≥ 80 % (based on caregiver report and pharmacy refill data) is required before adding a third agent; otherwise the strategy is to optimise dosing or simplify the existing regimen.  \n- Formulation substitution precedes any change of active drug: when syrup is unaffordable or out of stock, switch to equivalent tablets or dispersible formulation rather than selecting a different AED.  \n- Valproate inhibition of CYP enzymes can raise plasma levels of concurrent antiretrovirals and zidovudine; phenobarbital induction can reduce efficacy of antimalarials and protease‑inhibitor‑based ART, so drug‑interaction checks are mandatory when co‑prescribing.  \n- In infants < 2 years, valproate carries a higher risk of hepatotoxicity and hyperammonemia; baseline and repeat LFTs and ammonia should be obtained before initiation and after any dose increase.  \n- Cost‑effectiveness hierarchy for adjuncts: phenobarbital (cheapest, widely available) is preferred over levetiracetam when an adjunct is required and no sedation or interaction contraindications exist.  \n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window and no safety concerns are present, the recommended next step is to maintain the current valproate dose unchanged.",
  "candidate_learnings": "- Valproate syrup, tablets or dispersible are stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies and is the preferred first‑line AED for children ≤ 2 years with generalized or focal seizures when liver enzymes, platelet count and ammonia are normal.  \n- In children > 2 years with generalized seizures, valproate remains the first‑line choice if it is affordable and available; levetiracetam is considered only when valproate is contraindicated, poorly tolerated, or unavailable.  \n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory epilepsy or when both valproate and levetiracetam cannot be used; it is avoided in children with spastic cerebral palsy because of a high risk of sedation.  \n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) are avoided in any child with a documented drug‑induced rash; in the absence of a rash history they remain viable first‑line options for focal seizures.  \n- Clobazam is rarely stocked and not listed on the Ugandan Essential Medicines List; it is continued only if explicitly prescribed by the clinician and the caregiver can obtain serum level monitoring.  \n- When a prescribed formulation is unavailable or unaffordable, the priority is to substitute an equivalent tablet or dispersible preparation before switching to a different active drug.  \n- Adherence below 80 % (based on caregiver report or pharmacy refill data) triggers counseling and dose optimisation rather than addition of a third AED.  \n- Dose adjustments for valproate are made only after confirming a sub‑therapeutic serum level (< 50 µg/mL) and normal baseline ALT/AST, bilirubin and platelet count; modest overshoot of the therapeutic window (≤ 5 % above 30 mg/kg/day) is acceptable when seizure control is achieved and formulations limit exact dosing.  \n- Valproate inhibition of CYP enzymes can increase plasma levels of concurrent antiretrovirals or zidoviedine; phenobarbital induction can reduce efficacy of antimalarials and protease‑inhibitor‑based ART, so drug‑interaction checks are mandatory before any regimen change.  \n- In infants < 2 years, valproate carries higher risk of hepatotoxicity and hyperammonemia; baseline and repeat LFTs and ammonia should be obtained before initiation and after any dose increase.  \n- Cost‑effectiveness hierarchy for adjunct therapy places phenobarbital as the cheapest option, followed by levetiracetam; adjuncts are added only after adequate therapeutic dosing of the primary AED and documented breakthrough seizures.  \n- Children with comorbidities such as Down syndrome, congenital heart disease or cerebral palsy are managed with the same first‑line drugs but require careful monitoring for hepatic toxicity, sedation and drug‑interaction risks.  \n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window and no safety concerns are documented, the guideline‑driven next step is to maintain the current regimen unchanged.  \n- Frequent stock‑outs of dispersible levetiracetam tablets lead clinicians to prefer valproate or phenobarbital in resource‑limited settings.  \n- Laboratory monitoring (LFTs, platelet count, ammonia) is often unavailable; in such cases clinicians default to maintaining an effective dose rather than reducing it solely based on mg/kg targets.",
  "rejected_learnings": "- Valproate syrup, tablets or dispersible are stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies and is the preferred first‑line AED for children ≤ 2 years with generalized or focal seizures when liver enzymes, platelet count and ammonia are normal.  \n- In children > 2 years with generalized seizures, valproate remains the first‑line choice if it is affordable and available; levetiracetam is considered only when valproate is contraindicated, poorly tolerated, or unavailable.  \n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory epilepsy or when both valproate and levetiracetam cannot be used; it is avoided in children with spastic cerebral palsy because of a high risk of sedation.  \n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) are avoided in any child with a documented drug‑induced rash; in the absence of a rash history they remain viable first‑line options for focal seizures.  \n- Clobazam is rarely stocked and not listed on the Ugandan Essential Medicines List; it is continued only if explicitly prescribed by the clinician and the caregiver can obtain serum level monitoring.  \n- When a prescribed formulation is unavailable or unaffordable, the priority is to substitute an equivalent tablet or dispersible preparation before switching to a different active drug.  \n- Adherence below 80 % (based on caregiver report or pharmacy refill data) triggers counseling and dose optimisation rather than addition of a third AED.  \n- Dose adjustments for valproate are made only after confirming a sub‑therapeutic serum level (< 50 µg/mL) and normal baseline ALT/AST, bilirubin and platelet count; modest overshoot of the therapeutic window (≤ 5 % above 30 mg/kg/day) is acceptable when seizure control is achieved and formulations limit exact dosing.  \n- Valproate inhibition of CYP enzymes can increase plasma levels of concurrent antiretrovirals or zidoviedine; phenobarbital induction can reduce efficacy of antimalarials and protease‑inhibitor‑based ART, so drug‑